Higher Order Numerical Discretization Methods with Sobolev
Norm Minimization
S. Chandrasekarana , K. R. Jayaramana,‚àó, M. Gub , H. N. Mhaskarc , J. MoÔ¨Étta
a Dept.

of Electrical and Computer Engineering, University of California, Santa Barbara
b Dept. of Mathematics, University of California, Berkeley
c Dept. of Mathematics, California State University, Los Angeles

Abstract
This paper presents a method of producing higher order discretization weights for linear diÔ¨Äerential and integral
operators using the Minimum Sobolev Norm idea[1][2] in arbitrary geometry and grid conÔ¨Ågurations. The weight
computation involves solving a severely ill-conditioned weighted least-squares system. A method of solving this
system to very high-accuracy is also presented, based on the theory of Vavasis et al [3]. An end-to-end planar partial
diÔ¨Äerential equation solver is developed based on the described method and results are presented. Results presented
include the solution error, discretization error, condition number and time taken to solve several classes of equations
on various geometries. These results are then compared with those obtained using the Matlab‚Äôs FEM based PDE
Solver as well as Dealii[4].
Keywords: PDE Solver, Numerical Discretization, Sobolev Norm, Higher Order, Finite DiÔ¨Äerence, weighted least
squares, parallelism, Python

1. Introduction
This paper introduces a higher order Ô¨Ånite diÔ¨Äerence scheme for solving two dimensional elliptic PDEs based
on Minimum Sobolev Norm (MSN) interpolation[1][2]. The MSN scheme is a higher order interpolation idea, that
suppresses Runge Oscillations by minimizing an appropriately set up Sobolev Norm of the interpolant. We extend the
idea to setup a weighted least squares problem for weights that approximate linear diÔ¨Äerential and integral operators.
The ill-conditioned system that arises in the process is solved using a Complete Orthogonal Decomposition method.
We present a simple, yet eÔ¨Äective orthogonal decomposition method that we call CODA. With a method to approximate diÔ¨Äerential operators in hand, we present a local Finite DiÔ¨Äerence like method to solve planar elliptic PDEs. The
method described in this paper is fairly generic, basis independent and extends to variable coeÔ¨Écient, higher order
and higher dimensional problems easily.
